<br />
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">I think everybody knows by now how to play wraiths.  Wraiths are enduring, so they&#39;re better exhausted. Swept away prevents your uber strong wraiths from being wounded. Because this is powerful, you need to add threats as a cost. Stronger and more terrible removes those threats. Very simple, and it sounds really good. There is a catch though. swept away can be discarded, and or a wraith can be overwhelmed, setting off a potential barrage of threats. but thats when the new Gandalf card &quot;salve&quot; comes in. So you dont have swept away and the king of the dead is losing to.., lets say the witch king, (kotd is exhausted by the way). He would otherwise die, but you of course played salve on him the prior fellowship phase. So the king lives, and the threats dont go off ruining your day. <br />
<br />
The deck is a basic wraith deck with Gandalf (no more servant of course). The only thing new and fun is salve.<br />
<br />
The shadow side is much more experimental and weird. The plan is to use shapes to return companions back to the hand, and then exert the ringbearer with the witch king when they come back, thus making his cost cheaper. this way you can either play the witch king for less, or corrupt the ring-bearer. Surrounded by wraiths is in their too add extra twilight. With that and dark approach, you should be playing out tons of Nazgul too use shapes with<br />
<br />
The site path was made to mostly help out the Nazgul. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
